West plays 4\S. North leads the \DJ.

Losers: \S 2/3 : \H 0 : \D 1 : \C 0 : Total = 3/4

You are definitely going to lose the \DA and the \S A K. Therefore you must plan to avoid losing a third \S.

You should lead UP TO your honor cards. Cover the \DJ and lose to South's \DA. Win his return (probably another \D) in dummy. Lead a small \S to your \SJ. North wins with an honor and probably plays the \DT. Ruff it, lead a \C to dummy and lead the last \S. If South plays the other high honor you play low. If South plays low you guess whether to play the \SK, or \ST. Your best play is to assume the two honors were split and play the \SQ.

Now  for an alternate possible. 

You might think that North is just as likely to have held an original doubleton \S A K as doubleton \S A T, and that playing the \S9 would be as good a play as \SQ.

This is untrue for a very classy-named reason - The Principle of Restricted Choice. You may not even believe it when you read it, but it's mathematically sound. If North were dealt an original \S A K, he would have been just as likely to win with the \SK as with the \SA. The fact that he actually won the \SA makes it less likely that he also holds the \SK.}
